        "content": "type: search_result\ntitle: Exactly How To Spend One Day In Lisbon (for First Timers)\nurl: \"https://wheatlesswanderlust.com/one-day-in-lisbon/\"\ndescription: \"It’s served in either a small shot glass or an edible chocolate cup – get the dark chocolate cup for a tasty afternoon pick-me-up. ... Igreja de São Domingos while in Rossio. The historic 13th-century church is free to enter and you can see the damage from two earthquakes and a large fire that broke out in the building. Finally, round off your day in Lisbon by wandering up through the Alfama district.\"\npage_age: \"December 28, 2024\"\nprofile_name: Wheatless Wanderlust\nmeta_url_favicon: \"https://imgs.search.brave.com/yJQtA-pTiikR3MpZu2KRXXhYoX5aFJfFrtFuAEuls8c/rs:fit:32:32:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cDovL2Zhdmlj/b25zLnNlYXJjaC5i/cmF2ZS5jb20vaWNv/bnMvYjIzMjcyMDg5/ZTM4NzQ0OTQwODk1/OTk2OWM2MjkyYWQ1/ZTM1MTkwMjI2MDIz/MTFlNzU3Y2M0MGJi/NTBkYzRlZi93aGVh/dGxlc3N3YW5kZXJs/dXN0LmNvbS8\"\nthumbnail_src: \"https://imgs.search.brave.com/hsTqSDmEwFo362_yBZ8qD5YvjsQNjkrfKlMq3G5wA9A/rs:fit:200:200:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cHM6Ly93aGVh/dGxlc3N3YW5kZXJs/dXN0LmNvbS93cC1j/b250ZW50L3VwbG9h/ZHMvMjAyMy8wMS9U/b3JyZS1kZS1CZWxl/bS5qcGc\"\nthumbnail_original: \"https://wheatlesswanderlust.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Torre-de-Belem.jpg\"\nextra_snippets: \"With just one day, we’d focus on three main areas; Belém, Chiado, and Alfama. Plus, make sure you try some canned fish and pasteis de nata and check out plenty of miradouros (viewpoints) along the way. In this one day Lisbon itinerary, we’ll help you cover all of the above and more.|If you’re leaving Lisbon this evening, you can finish this one day itinerary here. But if you’re not leaving the city until the following morning, end your day with some well-deserved drinks in the Graça district. Graça is another of Lisbon’s oldest neighborhoods, sitting on the highest hill in the capital, just a few blocks from Alfama and the Castelo de São Jorge. As well as being home to some of the city’s best viewpoints – such as Miradouro da Senhora do Monte, which is another great spot for sunset if you don’t want to pay entry for the castle – the neighborhood has many charming and authentic bars and restaurants that are much less touristy than those of nearby Alfama.|Lisbon is a charming city with countless viewpoints from its many hills across sweeping vistas of the city and the Tagus River. Combine that beauty with a rich history and culture (the age of exploration was part of Portugal’s golden age), an eclectic food scene thanks to a bounty of fresh ingredients (including seafood), and warm and friendly people, and we’re pretty sure you’re going to love Lisbon, just like we did.|It’s served in either a small shot glass or an edible chocolate cup – get the dark chocolate cup for a tasty afternoon pick-me-up. ... Igreja de São Domingos while in Rossio. The historic 13th-century church is free to enter and you can see the damage from two earthquakes and a large fire that broke out in the building. Finally, round off your day in Lisbon by wandering up through the Alfama district.\"\nhash: 4f26547f521d43f8\nembed_ref: wheatlesswanderlust.com-WUu\napp_id: web\nskill_id: search",
