        "type": "website",
        "content": "type: search_result\ntitle: \"How I spent one perfect day in Lisbon: Best first-timer itinerary 2026\"\nurl: \"https://www.sunshineseeker.com/destinations/lisbon/\"\ndescription: \"This guided afternoon food and wine tour takes the guesswork out of it and lets you try a whole range of Portuguese favorites — things like codfish cakes, chouriço, bifana, petiscos, and ginjinha — while also learning more about Lisbon’s ...\"\npage_age: 1 month ago\nprofile_name: Sunshine Chinese Seeker\nmeta_url_favicon: \"https://imgs.search.brave.com/Lt5HJsI_A-40gw4jFfKlo3UFfxTY3e8y8wH8G5ZfHvU/rs:fit:32:32:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cDovL2Zhdmlj/b25zLnNlYXJjaC5i/cmF2ZS5jb20vaWNv/bnMvYjY1NGRmNjU4/YWE5OTRkY2E5MmY0/ODkxNDBkNzkyYzZi/NTZjNjM1OWJjOTY2/NzA1NTUwZDkwOGRm/N2U4ODk3NC93d3cu/c3Vuc2hpbmVzZWVr/ZXIuY29tLw\"\nthumbnail_src: \"https://imgs.search.brave.com/VSGmssXprTvmQJV74J-NTKVLIrUqeyT89B2KskdE22s/rs:fit:200:200:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu/c3Vuc2hpbmVzZWVr/ZXIuY29tL3dwLWNv/bnRlbnQvdXBsb2Fk/cy8yMDI2LzAzL0xp/c2Jvbi1IaWdobGln/aHRzLUl0aW5lcmFy/eS53ZWJw\"\nthumbnail_original: \"https://www.sunshineseeker.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Lisbon-Highlights-Itinerary.webp\"\nextra_snippets: \"If there's one city I never get tired of returning to, it's Lisbon. I love the soft pastel colors, the tiled facades, the patterned pavements, the rattling yellow trams, and all those viewpoints looking out over terracotta rooftops and the|Start your days early. Lisbon is incredibly popular, especially from spring through autumn. Visiting viewpoints and historic areas like Alfama in the morning means fewer crowds, better light for photos, and a much more relaxed experience.|If you’re anything like me and tend to plan trips around food, a food tour is such a fun dinner option in Lisbon. The city has an amazing food scene, but unless you really know where to go, it’s easy to miss some of the most traditional spots. This guided afternoon food and wine tour takes the guesswork out of it and lets you try a whole range of Portuguese favorites — things like codfish cakes, chouriço, bifana, petiscos, and ginjinha — while also learning more about Lisbon’s food culture from a local.|I could not have dinner after the food tour, but if you’d rather go to a restaurant, I recommend Le 17.45 in Bairro Alto, or nearby. This is a great area to soak up Lisbon at night, whether you want a relaxed dinner, a wine bar, or a rooftop.\"\nhash: 1d96bbab525129c5\nembed_ref: sunshineseeker.com-vSo\napp_id: web\nskill_id: search",
